{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9fb9f681-f6d5-4060-9ee5-8b17a9a1eaf2","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Example usage:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod, Ignore(\"Blocked by issue #123\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Blocked by issue #123\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test, Ignore(\"Blocked by issue #123\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test, Skip(\"Blocked by issue #123\")]\npublic async Task MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\nKey difference: xUnit embeds the skip reason in the test attribute itself (`Skip` property), while the others use a separate attribute.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f426202e-fcef-4d88-90a1-204a79e34421","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":300,"requestId":"0423:1EAE:1E79C8:2C9BFB:69E81E34"},"id":"0ccd42db-3045-4ec4-8c2a-18456ac6d07e","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:02:51.787Z","parentId":"2a330e4d-1e58-4e96-ba44-9d02a425e6c6"}
